{
  "text": "Research utilizing fNIRS to examine neural correlates of object processing in infancy has provided support for the possibility that regions of temporal cortex are involved in infant VWM for occluded objects (e.g., [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . For example, [CITATION_4] tested 3-to 5-and 11-to 12-mo-old infants in an occlusion task in which objects moved behind a screen and then reappeared on the other side of the screen. Infants were tested in three conditions: shape difference, color difference, or control. In the shape-difference condition, the object changed shape but not color on reappearance. In the color-difference condition, the object changed color but not shape. The object remained unchanged in the control condition.",
